WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.799 --> 00:00:01.496
Nina: Hi, Sal.

00:00:01.496 --> 00:00:03.103
So, tell us a little bit about your book

00:00:03.103 --> 00:00:05.189
and the journey that you underwent

00:00:05.189 --> 00:00:07.128
before you started the Khan Academy,

00:00:07.128 --> 00:00:08.674
which led you to writing this book.

00:00:09.243 --> 00:00:10.434
Sal:Yeah, well, the book is ...

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:13.547
Well, it's a little bit about that journey

00:00:13.547 --> 00:00:18.316
but really how that journey informed
what Khan Academy has now become

00:00:18.316 --> 00:00:20.744
and then, how that could inform what maybe

00:00:21.728 --> 00:00:24.200
classrooms could become or
what learning could become

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:25.687
and not in just a kind of

00:00:25.702 --> 00:00:27.174
pie in the sky kind of way

00:00:27.174 --> 00:00:28.662
but I know, this is really happening

00:00:28.662 --> 00:00:31.527
and it really feels like
we're at this inflection point

00:00:31.527 --> 00:00:33.856
in what's going on in classrooms,.

00:00:34.902 --> 00:00:36.939
This whole

00:00:36.939 --> 00:00:38.806
adventure for me started somewhat,

00:00:38.806 --> 00:00:40.799
actually, very inadvertently (chuckles),

00:00:40.799 --> 00:00:46.113
it was 2004, I was working as an
analyst at a hedge fund at the time.

00:00:46.666 --> 00:00:48.045
I've just gotten married.

00:00:48.045 --> 00:00:50.779
Family from New Orleans is visiting
me in Boston after my wedding

00:00:50.779 --> 00:00:55.493
and it turned out, this one
cousin Nadia was having trouble,

00:00:55.493 --> 00:00:58.596
12-years-old, I had
trouble believing that.

00:00:58.596 --> 00:01:00.873
She's an extremely bright girl.

00:01:01.549 --> 00:01:05.139
Nina: (laughs)

00:01:05.171 --> 00:01:09.084
And when I asked her about,

00:01:09.084 --> 00:01:11.114
actually, her mom who told
me and I asked Nadia about it

00:01:11.114 --> 00:01:13.136
and she said, "Oh, yeah. I'm
having trouble with units."

00:01:13.136 --> 00:01:15.050
and I said,

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:16.380
"Let me tutor you."

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:18.004
I think she thought I was just bluffing.

00:01:18.004 --> 00:01:19.673
So, I said, "No, we're
gonna work this out."

00:01:19.673 --> 00:01:21.175
She went back to New Orleans.

00:01:21.175 --> 00:01:22.479
Got her on the phone.

00:01:22.479 --> 00:01:24.146
We ended up using some
tools on the internet

00:01:24.146 --> 00:01:26.170
so that we could see each
other scroll initially

00:01:26.170 --> 00:01:28.708
with a mouse and we got these
little pen tablet things

00:01:28.708 --> 00:01:29.661
and

00:01:29.661 --> 00:01:33.170
long story short, she went
from being a struggling student

00:01:33.170 --> 00:01:38.065
to catching up with her class and
then becoming somewhat advanced

00:01:38.065 --> 00:01:40.949
Nina: (laughs)

00:01:40.949 --> 00:01:43.683
I called her school and I said,
"I really think Nadia needs

00:01:43.683 --> 00:01:47.190
"to retake a placement exam."
and they said, "Who are you?"

00:01:47.190 --> 00:01:49.351
Nina: (laughs)

00:01:49.351 --> 00:01:53.355
but you know, I then started
tutoring her brothers

00:01:53.355 --> 00:01:57.658
and fast forward, two years, we got
around, free tutoring was happening.

00:01:57.658 --> 00:02:00.494
I was tutoring 10, 15
family, friends, cousins

00:02:00.494 --> 00:02:03.610
and it was at that point that a

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:06.535
and the firm, I was working for,

00:02:06.535 --> 00:02:08.893
it was a firm but it was
my boss and his dog and me.

00:02:08.893 --> 00:02:12.764
We moved to Silicon Valley
and I was telling a friend

00:02:12.764 --> 00:02:14.824
about all the stuff I
was doing with my cousins

00:02:14.824 --> 00:02:18.522
and he said well, and I was complaining
that it's getting hard to scale.

00:02:18.522 --> 00:02:19.902
I still had a day job.

00:02:19.902 --> 00:02:21.932
There's all these students around
the country with time zones

00:02:21.932 --> 00:02:23.802
and etc., etc. and he
said, "Why don't you make

00:02:24.441 --> 00:02:27.544
"some tutorials to come up on YouTube?"

00:02:27.544 --> 00:02:30.351
and I thought that was a silly idea.

00:02:30.351 --> 00:02:33.771
Nina: (chuckles)

00:02:33.771 --> 00:02:37.524
but I gave it a shot and long story short,

00:02:37.524 --> 00:02:40.070
that kind of started
getting a ton of traction.

00:02:40.070 --> 00:02:41.539
People started looking at it.

00:02:41.539 --> 00:02:44.000
[unintelligible] I was also
was working on this little

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:45.662
software tool for my cousins.

00:02:45.662 --> 00:02:47.668
So there's this view that,
"Hey, maybe this could be

00:02:47.668 --> 00:02:50.528
"an institution to help
people." and so, we set it up,

00:02:50.528 --> 00:02:54.160
as a not-for-profit and then in 2009,
I had trouble focusing on my day job.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:57.321
So, I quit and started doing
Khan Academy full time.

00:02:57.321 --> 00:02:59.198
Nina: Also, tell me a little
bit about the Khan Academy.

00:02:59.198 --> 00:03:00.691
What is the business model?

00:03:00.691 --> 00:03:02.973
Let's start with the big,
hairy audacious goal,

00:03:02.973 --> 00:03:06.043
Sal: (laughs)

00:03:06.043 --> 00:03:09.323
and then the business model
that you've based it on.

00:03:09.753 --> 00:03:11.491
Sal: Yeah, so the ...

00:03:11.491 --> 00:03:12.959
Well, maybe I'll go the other way around

00:03:12.959 --> 00:03:14.541
because you know

00:03:14.541 --> 00:03:17.360
when I was starting all of these and I was
sitting in the middle of Silicon Valley.

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:19.665
I came from a very for-profit-reality.

00:03:20.695 --> 00:03:22.907
There are my friends who are
venture capitalists says,

00:03:22.907 --> 00:03:25.076
"Hey, Sal. You know we could fund this

00:03:25.076 --> 00:03:26.996
"and it could be this double
bottom line business."

00:03:26.996 --> 00:03:30.147
or whatever that means and there
was a lot of temptation there

00:03:30.147 --> 00:03:31.770
and there's nothing wrong with that

00:03:31.770 --> 00:03:33.188
but there was this feeling.

00:03:33.188 --> 00:03:35.481
You know, I was getting all
of these emotional reward

00:03:35.481 --> 00:03:37.723
from these thank-you letters
that people were sending me

00:03:37.723 --> 00:03:39.975
and the sense that, "Hey, I
was making these simple things

00:03:39.975 --> 00:03:41.813
"for my cousin and now you know."

00:03:41.813 --> 00:03:43.312
At first tens of thousands,
hundreds thousands

00:03:43.312 --> 00:03:45.915
and now, million of students
are using it around the world.

00:03:45.915 --> 00:03:48.830
I'd like this stuff to be around
in 100 years or in 500 years.

00:03:48.830 --> 00:03:53.501
I don't want this collection
of software and content

00:03:53.501 --> 00:03:55.136
and this organization.

00:03:55.136 --> 00:03:57.792
I don't want it to skew from
this mission of being able

00:03:57.792 --> 00:04:01.421
to reach these people and so,
when I look at other organizations

00:04:01.421 --> 00:04:05.554
in the universe that are able
to do that last many, many,

00:04:05.554 --> 00:04:09.108
hopefully, centuries and
stay true to their missions,

00:04:09.108 --> 00:04:11.277
it's a not-for-profit where
there is no ownership.

00:04:11.277 --> 00:04:16.199
It's a public charity and so
I said, "Well, I should set

00:04:16.199 --> 00:04:17.568
"this up as a not for profit."

00:04:17.568 --> 00:04:18.724
Not quite understanding what that is

00:04:18.724 --> 00:04:21.112
and I remember when I was doing
that initial paperwork for it,

00:04:21.112 --> 00:04:24.581
the IRS asks you, "What's your mission?"

00:04:24.581 --> 00:04:27.981
and I kind of thought about it
for maybe three or four minutes

00:04:27.981 --> 00:04:32.340
and I said, "Oh, a free world-class
education for anyone, anywhere."

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:34.005
Nina: Why not? (laughs)

00:04:34.005 --> 00:04:36.460
Well, you never want something
you could just check, it's done.

00:04:36.460 --> 00:04:37.965
It's an aspiration.

00:04:37.965 --> 00:04:40.124
And it was a very delusional
aspirational at the time

00:04:40.124 --> 00:04:42.123
when I was literally
operating out of the closet

00:04:42.876 --> 00:04:46.262
but yeah, and so the business
model is we're not a business,

00:04:46.262 --> 00:04:51.930
we're a 501C3 not for profit but
we still have to sustain ourselves

00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:55.499
and the way we want to because we always
want the learning side of education

00:04:55.499 --> 00:04:57.221
We always want that to
be free because we think

00:04:57.221 --> 00:04:58.781
that's what empowers people.

00:04:58.781 --> 00:05:03.159
It's primarily foundation and
philanthropist-driven so far

00:05:03.159 --> 00:05:06.861
but we do think there are ways
to sustain itself in other ways

00:05:06.861 --> 00:05:09.169
whether it's licensing
content or who knows what?

00:05:09.169 --> 00:05:12.002
We're trying to explore
that but we're pretty true

00:05:12.002 --> 00:05:13.331
to keeping the content free.

00:05:13.331 --> 00:05:13.825
Nina: Sure.

00:05:13.825 --> 00:05:16.416
How many students are
you serving right now?

00:05:16.416 --> 00:05:18.129
How many instructors?

00:05:18.129 --> 00:05:20.160
Can you give me a sense as to how large?

00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:21.678
Sal: Yeah, and so-

00:05:21.678 --> 00:05:25.080
Nina: And what's the typical profile
of someone who comes to your website?

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:26.130
Sal: Yeah.

00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:29.559
So, the organization itself are 36 people.

00:05:29.559 --> 00:05:32.609
We're still relatively small
but it feels huge for me

00:05:32.609 --> 00:05:35.380
because last year, we were 13 and
a year before that, we were one.

00:05:35.380 --> 00:05:39.364
(laughs) We've been growing
fast but in this past month,

00:05:39.364 --> 00:05:43.234
we've reached 7 million
students, unique students.

00:05:43.234 --> 00:05:45.268
We've reached a total
of 16 million unique.

00:05:45.268 --> 00:05:47.156
That's the way you measure
unique students on the web,

00:05:48.125 --> 00:05:53.829
delivered 180 million lessons, 700
million problems had been done on the site

00:05:53.829 --> 00:05:57.230
and it's students all over the world.

00:05:57.230 --> 00:06:00.317
It's pretty much every
country in the world.

00:06:00.317 --> 00:06:03.784
Someone has used the
Khan Academy in some way.

00:06:03.784 --> 00:06:08.859
20,000 teachers, as far as we can
tell from our data are using it

00:06:08.859 --> 00:06:12.261
in their classes or with their
cohorts in some type of ways.

00:06:12.261 --> 00:06:15.674
It's kind of crazy, I call it,

00:06:15.674 --> 00:06:18.492
it's surreal for where it came from.

00:06:18.492 --> 00:06:20.183
Nina: Yeah, let's talk a little bit about

00:06:20.183 --> 00:06:22.490
how a classroom or a school can use you

00:06:22.490 --> 00:06:24.648
with this concept of a flipped classroom.

00:06:25.124 --> 00:06:26.579
Explain that to our viewers.

00:06:26.579 --> 00:06:28.886
Sal: Yeah, and I'll do two things because

00:06:28.886 --> 00:06:31.722
as flipped classroom has somewhat
been tied to Khan Academy

00:06:31.722 --> 00:06:35.511
and it is an interesting idea
and it is I think a forward step

00:06:35.511 --> 00:06:37.724
but part of the whole point
of this whole book was

00:06:37.724 --> 00:06:40.877
to tell people that we're not
necessarily about this flip.

00:06:40.877 --> 00:06:44.297
We're actually about pushing the
envelope even further than the flip.

00:06:45.035 --> 00:06:49.346
In a flip model, right now, at
home you do problems traditionally.

00:06:49.346 --> 00:06:51.294
That's called homework
and then the classroom.

00:06:51.294 --> 00:06:53.233
A lot of time in a traditional classroom,

00:06:53.233 --> 00:06:57.973
we spent lectures and the
flip is in a [pre-date]

00:06:57.973 --> 00:07:00.567
Khan Academy early on at
these videos out there.

00:07:00.567 --> 00:07:02.728
Some teachers were telling me,
"Hey, you made a decent video

00:07:02.728 --> 00:07:06.795
"on meiosis or on you
know, projectile motion.

00:07:06.795 --> 00:07:08.687
"I don't have to give
that lecture anymore.

00:07:08.687 --> 00:07:10.774
"My students have been watching
it on their time and pace.

00:07:10.774 --> 00:07:15.040
"They can remediate without
taking up class time

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:16.696
"and then when they go to class,

00:07:16.696 --> 00:07:20.084
" that's when they can either
ask me questions, clarifications

00:07:20.084 --> 00:07:21.714
"and we can do problems together."

00:07:21.714 --> 00:07:24.792
So, what used to be homework, the
problem sets could now be done

00:07:24.792 --> 00:07:26.125
inside the classroom.

00:07:26.125 --> 00:07:29.425
And the advantage there is,
the real learning occurs

00:07:29.425 --> 00:07:32.133
when you do the engagement, when
you're doing the problem sets

00:07:32.133 --> 00:07:34.924
and I think traditionally,
students either don't do homework

00:07:34.924 --> 00:07:36.600
or have trouble doing homework
because there's no one

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:38.138
at home to help them out.

00:07:38.138 --> 00:07:39.505
Now, they're in the classroom.

00:07:39.505 --> 00:07:40.503
They have the teacher.

00:07:40.503 --> 00:07:42.977
They have their peers, which
is an underutilized resource

00:07:42.977 --> 00:07:44.235
in the classroom.

00:07:44.235 --> 00:07:46.230
Not only to help you but
when you help others,

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:47.478
you learn a lot better.

00:07:47.478 --> 00:07:51.282
And it also gives the teacher
lens on how the class is doing.

00:07:51.282 --> 00:07:54.640
When you're lecturing, it's very
hard to know where people are.

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:56.530
I mean you might be able to
pull them, ask a few questions

00:07:56.530 --> 00:07:57.529
but it's very hard.

00:07:57.529 --> 00:08:00.056
A lot of times, the students
are a little bit, blank faces

00:08:00.056 --> 00:08:01.971
but now, if you're doing
problem solving together,

00:08:01.971 --> 00:08:03.587
you can do much more,

00:08:03.587 --> 00:08:06.740
you can understand where
students are and diagnose them

00:08:06.740 --> 00:08:08.460
and so that's the flip.

00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:10.713
What used to be homework in the classroom,

00:08:10.713 --> 00:08:11.803
what used to be

00:08:11.803 --> 00:08:14.017
lectures, are now at home.

00:08:14.863 --> 00:08:16.469
Makes the classroom interactive,

00:08:16.469 --> 00:08:18.857
students can get lectures
at their time and pace.

00:08:18.857 --> 00:08:20.014
Great.

00:08:20.014 --> 00:08:22.981
What I focus on a lot in the book is,

00:08:22.981 --> 00:08:26.310
let's go even further
because still, even the flip,

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:29.825
assumes that all the students are
going to cover the same material

00:08:29.825 --> 00:08:33.366
at the same pace together
and what I talk a lot about,

00:08:33.366 --> 00:08:34.736
is this

00:08:34.736 --> 00:08:37.902
we've all been indoctrinated in the system

00:08:37.902 --> 00:08:39.841
and when I talk about the
system, I'm not talking about

00:08:39.841 --> 00:08:42.242
what should be the student/teacher ration

00:08:42.242 --> 00:08:44.035
or what charter or private or public.

00:08:44.035 --> 00:08:45.250
I'm talking about the system.

00:08:45.250 --> 00:08:49.068
I'm talking about grouping
kids by age-based cohorts.

00:08:49.345 --> 00:08:52.302
They cover certain subjects in a set pace.

00:08:52.302 --> 00:08:54.419
We grade them based on
their variable understanding

00:08:54.419 --> 00:08:56.052
and then we keep pushing them forward

00:08:56.052 --> 00:08:58.642
and we just assume that's what school is

00:08:58.642 --> 00:09:01.853
but what I go through
great lengths to show is,

00:09:01.853 --> 00:09:04.095
no, this is actually
relatively new phenomena.

00:09:04.095 --> 00:09:04.731
It's about 200 years.

00:09:04.731 --> 00:09:05.629
I mean, it's not that new.

00:09:05.629 --> 00:09:11.032
So, 200 years old that we inherited
from a country that no longer exists.

00:09:12.093 --> 00:09:16.151
Nina: The Prussians (chuckles).

00:09:16.151 --> 00:09:20.477
and even to us, I guess, it was

00:09:20.477 --> 00:09:22.961
during the Industrial
Revolution, was the first time

00:09:22.961 --> 00:09:26.664
that people seriously thought about,
"How can we educate everybody?"

00:09:26.664 --> 00:09:31.593
Before that, it was, you're the
son of a lord and you would get a,

00:09:31.593 --> 00:09:34.730
king and you get a private tutor and
the private tutor was a [goal] standard.

00:09:34.730 --> 00:09:37.838
They're working at your pace
and differentiating it for you

00:09:37.838 --> 00:09:39.802
but now, all of a sudden in
Prussia, there's like, "Okay,

00:09:39.802 --> 00:09:41.856
"we wanna have mass
education. How do we do it

00:09:41.856 --> 00:09:46.232
"in a practical way?" and whoa,
it's the Industrial Revolution.

00:09:46.232 --> 00:09:47.657
Well, how do we do anything
in a practical way?

00:09:47.657 --> 00:09:50.523
We stick them on an assembly
line and as they go through,

00:09:50.523 --> 00:09:52.524
we do something to the
product and then hopefully

00:09:52.524 --> 00:09:54.365
at the end, we have a decent product.

00:09:54.365 --> 00:09:57.497
And so, they essentially applied
the same model to classrooms.

00:09:57.497 --> 00:10:00.164
The kids are in these
brackets based on age.

00:10:00.164 --> 00:10:01.095
You know, it's funny.

00:10:01.095 --> 00:10:04.282
I was talking to a friend
and her child already knows

00:10:04.282 --> 00:10:06.165
how to read and everything and
she was trying to get the child

00:10:06.165 --> 00:10:07.420
into the kindergarten.

00:10:07.420 --> 00:10:08.876
He's like born in October or something and

00:10:09.583 --> 00:10:12.667
and the school said, "Oh yeah

00:10:12.667 --> 00:10:14.663
"he's a very bright kid
but you know, we can't.

00:10:14.663 --> 00:10:16.502
"He's too small."

00:10:16.502 --> 00:10:17.181
and I told my frie-

00:10:17.181 --> 00:10:19.001
and she came back, she's
like, "Yeah, he's too small."

00:10:19.001 --> 00:10:21.666
I was like, "Look, if that's
what they were concerned about,

00:10:21.666 --> 00:10:23.476
"they should be grouping them by size."

00:10:23.476 --> 00:10:28.724
That's (laughs) the obvious
natural, but so that's the model.

00:10:28.724 --> 00:10:32.232
And even the flip is in
the context of that model.

00:10:32.232 --> 00:10:33.974
On week three, we cover parabolas.

00:10:33.974 --> 00:10:37.224
Week four, we cover systems of
equations and even if you have,

00:10:37.224 --> 00:10:38.819
we give students grades.

00:10:38.819 --> 00:10:42.685
We give them a B and that B shows that
they have a gap in their knowledge,

00:10:42.685 --> 00:10:45.617
A C, even a D, you can get an exam
but then you move to the next topic.

00:10:45.617 --> 00:10:47.369
That's usually building on top of that,

00:10:47.369 --> 00:10:49.122
which is pretty much
dooming you to failure.

00:10:49.122 --> 00:10:49.783
Nina: Exactly.

00:10:49.783 --> 00:10:51.968
Sal: And so, what, I advocate strongly

00:10:51.968 --> 00:10:54.593
and we're already seeing this
in schools, trying to experiment

00:10:54.593 --> 00:10:57.996
or moving this direction is, if you
take lecture out of the classroom,

00:10:57.996 --> 00:10:59.934
there's no longer the need for everyone

00:10:59.934 --> 00:11:01.765
to move together at the same pace.

00:11:01.765 --> 00:11:04.514
And as soon as you get
rid of that assumption,

00:11:04.514 --> 00:11:07.267
you can completely rethink
what a classroom can be.

00:11:07.267 --> 00:11:09.231
You can start having everyone
run at their own pace,

00:11:09.231 --> 00:11:11.630
you can leverage class time
when humans are together

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:13.560
for actual interactivity.

00:11:13.560 --> 00:11:15.534
You can start saying, "Well,
why do we only have one teacher

00:11:15.534 --> 00:11:17.611
"in the room? Why can't we
have two teachers in the room?

00:11:17.611 --> 00:11:19.487
"Why do we have a bell ring?"

00:11:19.487 --> 00:11:20.943
and this bell ringing,
this is like a factory,

00:11:21.804 --> 00:11:23.489
in a 19th century factory.

00:11:23.489 --> 00:11:26.716
Why do we have a bell ringing that's
saying, "Stop what you're doing

00:11:26.716 --> 00:11:29.077
"on chemistry. You must
now start English."

00:11:29.077 --> 00:11:30.053
and we all know.

00:11:30.053 --> 00:11:31.278
Anyone who's done
anything creative because

00:11:31.278 --> 00:11:33.441
that's the best way to stop creativity,

00:11:33.441 --> 00:11:35.691
Nina: You're done.

00:11:35.691 --> 00:11:37.570
Nina: Move on.

00:11:37.570 --> 00:11:39.275
And so, what

00:11:39.275 --> 00:11:41.481
what we've advocating is move to reality

00:11:41.481 --> 00:11:44.522
with possibly the help of
tools like Khan Academy

00:11:44.522 --> 00:11:46.155
so that every student can
run at their own pace.

00:11:46.155 --> 00:11:49.407
Soon teachers have dashboards,
tools that empower them

00:11:49.407 --> 00:11:52.690
and that use class time for
interactivity and creativity.

00:11:52.690 --> 00:11:53.980
Nina: Right, right.

00:11:54.733 --> 00:11:56.527
You touched on this a little
bit but explain a little bit

00:11:56.527 --> 00:12:00.065
about why is it that your
platform has taken off

00:12:00.065 --> 00:12:03.286
and is getting so much attention, when
so many others were kind of trying

00:12:03.286 --> 00:12:05.400
to do the same thing
on the for-profit side,

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.739
some on the non-profit
side haven't succeeded.

00:12:07.739 --> 00:12:09.321
Sal: Yeah, it's an open question.

00:12:09.321 --> 00:12:12.059
It's a question which we're
constantly asking ourselves

00:12:12.059 --> 00:12:14.313
because we know whatever
the secret sauce is,

00:12:14.313 --> 00:12:16.422
we don't wanna lose it
somewhere in the process.

00:12:16.991 --> 00:12:22.101
My best guess of why there's
this initial way of traction

00:12:22.101 --> 00:12:27.850
from 2006 to 2007, even
it continuous to grow is,

00:12:27.850 --> 00:12:30.154
those first videos I
think it was fortunate

00:12:30.154 --> 00:12:33.522
that it was just some guy
making it for his cousins.

00:12:34.322 --> 00:12:36.356
Nina: They were easy to use.

00:12:36.356 --> 00:12:37.818
Nina: Or understand.

00:12:37.818 --> 00:12:38.856
They felt very human.

00:12:38.856 --> 00:12:40.786
And I think the big learning
is, is that people were hungry,

00:12:40.786 --> 00:12:42.774
I wasn't the first person
to make videos on YouTube.

00:12:42.774 --> 00:12:45.769
I wasn't the first person
to think of teaching,

00:12:45.769 --> 00:12:48.040
as soon as radio came out, people
were saying, "Oh, we'll use this

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:50.222
"to teach the world." and
then TV, "Oh, we'll use this

00:12:50.222 --> 00:12:51.496
"to teach the world." and VCR.

00:12:51.496 --> 00:12:53.062
Now, it's on demand.

00:12:53.062 --> 00:12:56.991
But historically, it was
either a videotape of someone

00:12:56.991 --> 00:13:00.892
at a chalkboard, traditional
class, which feels very,

00:13:00.892 --> 00:13:03.346
it feels distant even when
you're in the classroom.

00:13:03.346 --> 00:13:05.988
You're there, I'm over here,
the next step in the equation

00:13:05.988 --> 00:13:07.595
and you do it like that.

00:13:07.595 --> 00:13:09.514
So, that's very, not very [unintelligible]

00:13:09.514 --> 00:13:10.700
and we make that into video.

00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:11.754
It's even harder to see,

00:13:11.754 --> 00:13:13.538
"What are they writing there?
And I can't hear them."

00:13:14.722 --> 00:13:16.856
and these felt very personal.

00:13:17.332 --> 00:13:18.428
You're sitting next to me.

00:13:18.428 --> 00:13:22.187
I think the other dimension of
it is just a conversational tone.

00:13:23.710 --> 00:13:26.715
I think a lot of people, they
try to make it very polished,

00:13:26.715 --> 00:13:30.221
which is not bad but in that
process, you lose the humanity.

00:13:30.221 --> 00:13:32.611
So, it sounds like your
GPS system you know,

00:13:32.611 --> 00:13:34.215
"The next step with this
equation is when ... "

00:13:34.215 --> 00:13:38.570
and I think hopefully, this
is something that I try

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:40.533
to put into it is,

00:13:40.533 --> 00:13:42.459
one of the things I
think allowed me to do,

00:13:42.459 --> 00:13:45.826
to kind of thrive in math or
science and then eventually,

00:13:45.826 --> 00:13:49.081
even finance was, I felt like I had a
really holistic understanding of things

00:13:49.081 --> 00:13:52.095
and my basics were really,
really, really solid

00:13:52.095 --> 00:13:54.304
and then my basics in
algebra were really good.

00:13:54.304 --> 00:13:55.792
So, when I went into
calculus, I was like, "Oh

00:13:55.792 --> 00:13:58.577
"this is intuitive." and when
I went to corporate finance,

00:13:58.577 --> 00:14:00.745
I was like, "This is intuitive.
There's nothing new here."

00:14:01.606 --> 00:14:04.582
and you see all the really,
really smart people,

00:14:04.582 --> 00:14:06.003
they're just learning for the next exam,

00:14:06.003 --> 00:14:08.669
memorizing formulas then they
forget it and then when they see

00:14:08.669 --> 00:14:10.874
a related concept, it's
like, "What's this?"

00:14:10.874 --> 00:14:15.216
And so, what I tried in those
early days for my cousins is,

00:14:15.216 --> 00:14:18.336
give a sense of intuition, draw
the connections between things

00:14:18.336 --> 00:14:19.835
so that when they see this new concept,

00:14:19.835 --> 00:14:21.267
it's not some random new concept.

00:14:21.267 --> 00:14:23.087
It's connected to everything
they learned before

00:14:23.087 --> 00:14:26.975
and I get a lot of letters
and I would have assumed that

00:14:26.975 --> 00:14:30.669
that only been appealing to
the motivated kids so to speak

00:14:30.669 --> 00:14:33.859
but I get a lot of letters from
kids that were traditionally,

00:14:33.859 --> 00:14:36.114
disengaged or demotivated
and they said, "That's why

00:14:36.176 --> 00:14:38.737
"I was demotivated. No one
was explaining the why.

00:14:38.737 --> 00:14:40.907
"No one was giving me the connections."

00:14:40.907 --> 00:14:45.532
So, hopefully, that's why people
have been, I guess connecting

00:14:45.532 --> 00:14:46.652
to the content.

00:14:46.652 --> 00:14:49.740
Nina: Yeah, so let's talk a
little bit about virtual education

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:52.585
and offering the types of
things that you're offering.

00:14:52.585 --> 00:14:56.378
A lot of people are still a
little wary of these reforms.

00:14:56.378 --> 00:14:59.165
They see it as a mechanism to
ultimately get rid of teachers

00:14:59.165 --> 00:15:01.500
in the classroom or reduce class sizes.

00:15:01.500 --> 00:15:03.548
You talked a little bit
about this in the book

00:15:03.548 --> 00:15:05.137
and explain that a little bit.

00:15:05.137 --> 00:15:06.131
Sal: Yeah, yeah.

00:15:06.131 --> 00:15:07.693
No, I think that's a super important point

00:15:07.693 --> 00:15:11.216
because whenever, when we've
learned the last 15, 20 years

00:15:11.216 --> 00:15:14.260
Nina: They think about robot replacement.

00:15:14.260 --> 00:15:16.244
It's like, "Is that going
to replace the physically?

00:15:16.244 --> 00:15:18.355
The Barnes &amp; Noble versus Amazon.com,

00:15:18.355 --> 00:15:19.938
there's a natural contention there.

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:22.576
That's

00:15:22.576 --> 00:15:25.039
exact opposite of the way I think
is going to happen in education.

00:15:25.039 --> 00:15:28.570
Everything we do is not going
to replace a physical school.

00:15:28.570 --> 00:15:29.409
I have young kids.

00:15:29.409 --> 00:15:31.407
I want them to go to a physical school.

00:15:31.407 --> 00:15:33.075
I want them to get interaction.

00:15:33.075 --> 00:15:38.298
What it will do, is I think, give
all of our children the experience

00:15:38.298 --> 00:15:41.414
that I think every parent and every
teacher or every student wants

00:15:41.414 --> 00:15:44.850
to be a part of, and then even now,
we're going to physical experience

00:15:44.850 --> 00:15:46.493
but we're not leveraging the humans.

00:15:46.493 --> 00:15:48.817
We're going but for the most part,
people are sitting passively there

00:15:48.817 --> 00:15:49.958
and they're listening.

00:15:49.958 --> 00:15:53.905
It's hard for the teachers too
because it's hard to just speak

00:15:53.905 --> 00:15:56.677
for 60 minutes without getting
that connection with the students

00:15:56.677 --> 00:15:59.990
and so, what we're
advocating is leverage tools,

00:15:59.990 --> 00:16:02.514
so you can get maybe information
delivery out of the way.

00:16:02.514 --> 00:16:04.571
So you can get some of the
problem solving out of the way

00:16:04.832 --> 00:16:07.350
but so when people go
and they have class time,

00:16:07.350 --> 00:16:09.581
the scariest class time
with other human beings that

00:16:09.581 --> 00:16:12.370
that's optimally interactive and
not interactive in the web sense,

00:16:12.370 --> 00:16:14.001
interactive in the human sense.

00:16:14.001 --> 00:16:15.863
Class time is all conversation.

00:16:15.863 --> 00:16:19.456
Class time is all peer tutoring
and working with their teacher.

00:16:19.456 --> 00:16:24.092
Class time is all doing
open ended projects and so,

00:16:24.092 --> 00:16:27.091
I talk about this in the book
and I gave a Ted Talk a bunch,

00:16:27.598 --> 00:16:31.133
the irony here is I strongly believe
and it's not just talk again,

00:16:31.133 --> 00:16:33.350
we're seeing this in classrooms,

00:16:33.350 --> 00:16:34.758
is that

00:16:34.758 --> 00:16:36.906
you can actually use technology
to make the classroom more human

00:16:37.444 --> 00:16:38.685
and I'm very careful.

00:16:38.685 --> 00:16:40.344
You mentioned there's skepticism.

00:16:40.344 --> 00:16:41.428
I think there should be.

00:16:41.428 --> 00:16:42.595
I'm skeptical when someone says,

00:16:42.595 --> 00:16:45.235
"Hey, we just ordered
500 iPad for our school."

00:16:45.235 --> 00:16:47.100
and I say, "Well, what
are you gonna do with it?"

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:48.633
or, "How are you gonna integrate
it into the curriculum?"

00:16:48.633 --> 00:16:51.870
or, "How are you gonna leverage
it to fundamentally transform

00:16:51.870 --> 00:16:54.112
"what's going on?" and
there usually aren't a lot

00:16:54.112 --> 00:16:57.216
of answers there, and so, I
think it is good to be skeptical

00:16:57.216 --> 00:17:01.892
but at the same time, there
is, I think a reason for hope.

00:17:02.553 --> 00:17:05.382
Nina: How do you evaluate
the impact of your courses?

00:17:05.382 --> 00:17:08.555
Since again, you talked a little
bit about grades in your book

00:17:08.555 --> 00:17:10.137
and how you don't like
the concept of grading.

00:17:10.137 --> 00:17:12.503
How do you know that they
have actually worked?

00:17:12.503 --> 00:17:14.249
Sal: Yeah, and I'll tell you.

00:17:14.249 --> 00:17:16.971
I mean a lot of times, when I
grew up, I remember sometimes

00:17:16.971 --> 00:17:18.639
we meet people who said, 'I
don't believe in grades.'

00:17:18.639 --> 00:17:22.190
and I thought they were these kind of
like granola-bar hippie-type people

00:17:22.190 --> 00:17:26.659
that you know, and now, I think I
appreciate what they were saying.

00:17:26.659 --> 00:17:29.992
Grades, normally when you say
people who don't like grades,

00:17:29.992 --> 00:17:31.853
you really think, they're
being touchy-feely.

00:17:31.853 --> 00:17:33.288
They're not being rigorous

00:17:33.288 --> 00:17:36.115
but actually, they're saying
grades aren't rigorous enough.

00:17:36.115 --> 00:17:39.044
Grades are this thing that
give this feeling of rigor.

00:17:39.044 --> 00:17:41.592
Oh, A, B, A is , "Oh, you
really know your stuff."

00:17:41.592 --> 00:17:42.964
F, "You don't know your stuff."

00:17:42.964 --> 00:17:46.757
One, they're somewhat
arbitrary, depends on the test,

00:17:46.757 --> 00:17:48.235
depends on how it's measured.

00:17:48.235 --> 00:17:51.087
But even more than that,
when you give grades,

00:17:51.087 --> 00:17:52.275
especially, in the sense,

00:17:52.275 --> 00:17:56.184
if you got a C on an exam,
you have obvious weaknesses,

00:17:56.184 --> 00:17:57.730
assuming that it was even a good exam.

00:17:57.730 --> 00:17:59.288
You have obvious weaknesses.

00:17:59.995 --> 00:18:02.732
That should be used as an
assessment to say, "Okay,

00:18:02.732 --> 00:18:04.653
"you need to now improve
on those weaknesses,

00:18:04.653 --> 00:18:06.874
"before we move onto a more advance
topic." like it's common sense.

00:18:06.874 --> 00:18:11.733
Get your basics down but instead,
we use grades as a value judgment.

00:18:11.733 --> 00:18:14.252
"You're smart. You're dumb.
You're fast. You're slow."

00:18:14.252 --> 00:18:17.358
and that's just going to be
a self-fulfilling prophecy.

00:18:17.358 --> 00:18:21.348
So, what we say is, "No, let's just make
sure everyone masters every concept."

00:18:21.348 --> 00:18:23.617
So rather than having superficial
understanding of algebra

00:18:23.617 --> 00:18:27.050
and then moving onto trigonometry,
make sure you really understand

00:18:27.050 --> 00:18:30.628
algebra deeply and then trigonometry's
gonna make a lot more sense.

00:18:30.628 --> 00:18:32.947
It's gonna be a lot easier to learn
and if you master trigonometry

00:18:32.947 --> 00:18:37.188
then calculus is going to
start seeming very intuitive.

00:18:37.629 --> 00:18:40.890
In terms of how we're doing
it, we're working with schools,

00:18:40.890 --> 00:18:43.556
and famously, Los Altos, which
is now using Khan Academy.

00:18:43.556 --> 00:18:47.405
It's probably one of the best,
if not the best school district

00:18:47.405 --> 00:18:52.516
in the country is using Khan
Academy for 5th through 8th grade

00:18:52.516 --> 00:18:55.137
as one of the tools that they use .

00:18:55.137 --> 00:18:57.652
and there we have formal studies going on

00:18:57.652 --> 00:19:01.828
to understand exactly, how this is
impacting students and teachers,

00:19:01.828 --> 00:19:05.050
both objectively on things
like test scores and grades

00:19:05.050 --> 00:19:07.455
but also on things

00:19:07.455 --> 00:19:10.997
subjectively, "Are the teachers
more excited about their work?

00:19:10.997 --> 00:19:13.290
"Are the students more
excited about their work?"

00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:17.166
And then on top of that, we have
3 million problems down a day

00:19:17.166 --> 00:19:18.098
on our site.

00:19:18.098 --> 00:19:20.781
We have this huge number of students,
7 million a month using our site.

00:19:20.781 --> 00:19:23.683
We have this treasure trove
of data on our site itself.

00:19:23.683 --> 00:19:26.783
Nina: Monitoring it on a daily basis.

00:19:26.783 --> 00:19:29.555
Yeah, I mean all these other
web companies are able to do.

00:19:29.555 --> 00:19:31.949
We as a kind of education
not-for-profit can now do,

00:19:31.949 --> 00:19:35.075
using analytics,
optimizing for engagements,

00:19:35.075 --> 00:19:36.660
seeing what kind of learning is going on.

00:19:36.660 --> 00:19:37.825
Nina: Great, great.

00:19:37.825 --> 00:19:41.661
So, tell me a little bit
about, you gave a great

00:19:41.661 --> 00:19:45.165
historical overview of how we
came to educate students today,

00:19:45.165 --> 00:19:46.423
the way we're educating them.

00:19:46.423 --> 00:19:50.445
Did you always hold these
views and know this information

00:19:50.445 --> 00:19:54.606
before you stumbled on the
Khan Academy or this platform

00:19:54.606 --> 00:19:55.807
that you created?

00:19:55.807 --> 00:19:58.925
Or were these things that
you studied afterwards?

