But it was interesting
that even the research,

00:21:27.429 --> 00:21:29.804
the reasons why I made
the video so short is

00:21:29.804 --> 00:21:32.200
because YouTube limited
me to 10 minutes but then

00:21:32.738 --> 00:21:34.790
I used to have researchers
telling me, "No, there's actually

00:21:34.790 --> 00:21:38.292
"cognitive research that shows
..." and that's where a lot

00:21:38.292 --> 00:21:39.693
of that research from the book come from.

00:21:39.693 --> 00:21:43.500
Actually people, especially dance
academic content can't pay attention

00:21:43.500 --> 00:21:44.898
for more than 10 to 15 minutes.

00:21:44.898 --> 00:21:47.713
So, it starts as, "Wow,
so why are we doing this?

00:21:47.713 --> 00:21:50.102
"Why are we using class time,
this time with human beings

00:21:50.102 --> 00:21:52.682
"for these hour-long lectures,
sometimes 90-minute lectures,

00:21:52.682 --> 00:21:54.630
"can't we get people to interact more?"

00:21:54.630 --> 00:21:56.348
And the more I did
research, a lot of these

00:21:56.348 --> 00:21:59.842
kind of just basic common sense
ideas [gelled] with research

00:21:59.842 --> 00:22:01.013
and that's when you feel best about it

00:22:01.013 --> 00:22:03.048
because they are common, every,

00:22:03.048 --> 00:22:05.678
it's weird when research tells
you something very non-intuitive,

00:22:05.678 --> 00:22:08.311
but here it's telling you something
very, very, very intuitive

00:22:08.311 --> 00:22:11.510
and the only hard to grasp thing
is that we're indoctrinated

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:13.346
into a strange model.

00:22:13.346 --> 00:22:14.161
Nina: Right, right.

00:22:14.161 --> 00:22:15.864
It all make sense.

