Tell me a little bit
about your own education.

00:22:18.067 --> 00:22:20.913
I mean something despite
the regiment of the system

00:22:20.913 --> 00:22:22.846
that you grew up in, something
must have gone right.

00:22:22.846 --> 00:22:23.956
Was it a teacher?

00:22:23.956 --> 00:22:27.282
Was it your parents you think
who kind of built this sense

00:22:27.282 --> 00:22:30.675
of inquisitiveness or was it, yeah,

00:22:30.675 --> 00:22:34.265
did you go to a particular
type of school that was open

00:22:34.265 --> 00:22:36.555
to nurturing you as an individual

00:22:36.555 --> 00:22:39.471
and paying attention
to your specific needs?

00:22:39.471 --> 00:22:42.306
Or yeah, did none of
these things work and-

00:22:42.306 --> 00:22:42.793
Sal: Yeah, no, no, no.

00:22:42.793 --> 00:22:44.357
I mean I,

00:22:44.357 --> 00:22:47.013
Nina: (laughs)

00:22:47.013 --> 00:22:48.682
if I go and say that none
of that stuff played in.

00:22:48.682 --> 00:22:51.944
I mean I think there's probably
a bunch of different factors

00:22:51.944 --> 00:22:53.643
and I'm probably forgetting some of them.

00:22:53.643 --> 00:22:56.214
One, I was blessed to have an older sister

00:22:56.214 --> 00:22:59.716
who was a very good student,
so I think that projected,

00:22:59.716 --> 00:23:01.862
when I would walk into a classroom,

00:23:01.862 --> 00:23:04.470
the teachers would remember
my sister and say, "Oh, you're

00:23:04.470 --> 00:23:06.656
"Farrah's sis- you're Farrah's
brother, you must be."

00:23:06.656 --> 00:23:09.662
and I was like in speech
therapy and stuff when I was,

00:23:09.662 --> 00:23:12.597
they would project that and
there's actually now studies

00:23:12.597 --> 00:23:14.466
that show that that projection
has huge implications

00:23:14.466 --> 00:23:15.511
for your own self-esteem.

00:23:15.511 --> 00:23:17.266
That was luck.

00:23:17.266 --> 00:23:20.354
On top of that, I went to just a,

00:23:20.354 --> 00:23:22.645
I would say it was a public
school in Jefferson Parish,

00:23:22.645 --> 00:23:25.720
public schools in Jefferson Parish
right outside of New Orleans.

00:23:25.720 --> 00:23:29.015
I would say it was the average
American public schools.

00:23:29.015 --> 00:23:31.606
All of them, elementary,
middle and high school

00:23:31.606 --> 00:23:34.906
but there were some
incredible teachers there.

00:23:34.906 --> 00:23:39.438
I think in high school in particular,
Mr. Hernandez, Miss Kennedy,

00:23:39.438 --> 00:23:41.906
Miss Kennedy was a journalism
teacher and actually, I would say

00:23:41.906 --> 00:23:45.015
that's where a lot of the ideas that
look, class should not be a lecture,

00:23:45.015 --> 00:23:47.029
class should be working
alongside the teacher.

00:23:47.029 --> 00:23:49.830
It was journalism class, so we
had a product, a creative product

00:23:49.830 --> 00:23:50.999
and newspaper to work on.

00:23:50.999 --> 00:23:53.006
I was the art editor and
she would give us feedback

00:23:53.006 --> 00:23:56.124
and she was like our senior peer
and I remember those interactions

00:23:56.124 --> 00:23:57.877
and a lot of the experience
that I got from journalism.

00:23:57.877 --> 00:24:00.838
I still think about it when
I'm working on Khan Academy.

00:24:01.745 --> 00:24:03.419
I think early in my schooling,

00:24:03.419 --> 00:24:06.169
I think this was key and also lucky,

00:24:06.169 --> 00:24:08.388
I got into you know, I don't
know what they call it now,

00:24:08.388 --> 00:24:10.756
these GT programs and what they did is,

00:24:10.756 --> 00:24:15.527
you have this very structured Prussian
curriculum for most of the day,

00:24:15.527 --> 00:24:17.693
but then one day, a week, they take
you out of a different classroom

00:24:17.693 --> 00:24:19.477
and they take you to these GT classrooms

00:24:19.477 --> 00:24:22.612
and there, you're going to this
classroom, which is essentially,

00:24:22.612 --> 00:24:25.862
the kind of classroom that
ideally, everyone should have.

00:24:25.862 --> 00:24:28.794
It was actually Miss
[Roselle] and Miss [Crouse].

00:24:28.794 --> 00:24:31.103
These two teachers and
they had PhDs in education

00:24:31.103 --> 00:24:34.723
and I remember the first day walking to GT

00:24:34.723 --> 00:24:37.321
and Miss [Roselle] says,
"What do you wanna do?"

00:24:37.321 --> 00:24:39.815
and I was like eight and I was like

00:24:41.368 --> 00:24:43.682
"I like to draw." and then
she says, "Well, you should

00:24:43.682 --> 00:24:46.685
"draw more then." and then she
introduced me to these things,

00:24:46.685 --> 00:24:49.090
different styles, different tools to draw,

00:24:49.090 --> 00:24:51.342
"What else are you interested
in?" and I was like,

00:24:51.342 --> 00:24:54.392
"I like puzzles." and she's like,
"Well, here's some puzzles."

00:24:54.392 --> 00:24:57.105
She would give me these brainteasers
and so she was mentoring me

00:24:57.105 --> 00:24:59.308
and it was self-pace and I
was able to go to my own pace

00:24:59.308 --> 00:25:00.939
and there was other kids
working on interesting things

00:25:00.939 --> 00:25:02.442
and I would get inspired by them.

00:25:02.442 --> 00:25:03.866
Sometimes, we would work on things

00:25:03.866 --> 00:25:06.609
and I think we needed that
breathing room to have re-

00:25:07.439 --> 00:25:10.703
I wonder if I didn't have that
experience early on in my life,

00:25:10.703 --> 00:25:14.246
whether I would have had the
ability to kind of self-direct

00:25:14.246 --> 00:25:17.174
or the ability to say, "Oh,
let me solve that problem."

00:25:17.174 --> 00:25:19.801
No one you know, that's an
interesting thing to tackle.

00:25:19.801 --> 00:25:20.567
Nina: Right.

00:25:20.567 --> 00:25:24.013
So along those lines, do you have
any advice for parents out there

00:25:24.013 --> 00:25:27.387
1st grader, 2nd graders
and I'm asking you this

00:25:27.387 --> 00:25:30.346
because in your book, you also
highlight how a lot of students

00:25:30.346 --> 00:25:33.730
in Southeast Asia, go to
school in order to show off

00:25:33.730 --> 00:25:36.820
what they know, not
necessarily to learn in school.

00:25:36.820 --> 00:25:40.070
Are there habits that you
think parents can start

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:44.932
to put in place early on, despite how
the schools are approaching education?

00:25:44.932 --> 00:25:47.254
Sal: Yeah, and take everything
I say with a grain of salt.

00:25:47.254 --> 00:25:48.572
I have a three-year-old
and a one-year-old,

00:25:48.572 --> 00:25:50.517
Nina: (laughs)

00:25:50.517 --> 00:25:51.911
of seven or eight-year-olds (laughs).

00:25:51.911 --> 00:25:54.023
I'm proud to get my one-year-old
off of the pacifier (laughs).

00:25:54.023 --> 00:25:56.689
Nina: Well, now that you
know, iPads are very popular. 

00:25:56.689 --> 00:25:58.081
Sal: You're absolutely right.

00:25:58.081 --> 00:26:01.379
Sal: I mean my sense, having
kind of gone through the system

00:26:01.379 --> 00:26:03.715
and even we're observing, we're
working with a lot of teachers,

00:26:03.715 --> 00:26:05.302
we're working with a lot of schools now,

00:26:05.302 --> 00:26:06.953
I would say there's a
couple of dimensions here.

00:26:06.953 --> 00:26:08.528
I think it is true.

00:26:08.528 --> 00:26:11.367
Asians whether it's East
Asian or South Asian,

00:26:12.829 --> 00:26:16.397
there is a culture of school
is where you go to show

00:26:16.397 --> 00:26:18.192
what you've already learned at home.

00:26:18.192 --> 00:26:21.275
I think that gives those
students an advantage of having

00:26:21.275 --> 00:26:26.323
this kind of buffer of their
learning stuff maybe ahead

00:26:26.323 --> 00:26:28.235
and I'm not saying that
necessarily has to be the way

00:26:28.235 --> 00:26:30.691
but it is a way to
ensure that your student

00:26:30.691 --> 00:26:33.031
in the Prussian model, doesn't get,

00:26:33.031 --> 00:26:34.931
falls behind and as soon
as they fall behind,

00:26:34.931 --> 00:26:37.199
all of these negative
self-perception things

00:26:37.199 --> 00:26:38.848
and they start to reinforce each other.

00:26:40.078 --> 00:26:43.150
I would do, I mean I'll
tell you what I would do

00:26:43.150 --> 00:26:43.675
with my own children.

00:26:43.675 --> 00:26:47.818
I would do some combination of
engaging them with a lot of the content

00:26:47.818 --> 00:26:49.759
in a way before it becomes stressful

00:26:51.682 --> 00:26:54.178
When I was teaching Nadia, algebra

00:26:54.178 --> 00:26:55.837
when she was in algebra class,
it was stressful for her

00:26:55.837 --> 00:26:57.133
because she's like, "I need to catch up.

00:26:57.133 --> 00:26:58.729
"I have an exam on it."

00:26:58.729 --> 00:27:00.518
When I started teaching
algebra to her younger brother

00:27:00.518 --> 00:27:02.770
who's in 5th grade, he thought it was fun

00:27:02.770 --> 00:27:04.058
because there's no stress here.

00:27:04.058 --> 00:27:05.601
It was just a fun thing
his cousin was teaching.

00:27:05.601 --> 00:27:08.602
At least expose your kids
to the ideas in algebra

00:27:08.602 --> 00:27:10.897
and physics and biology
and chemistry early on

00:27:10.897 --> 00:27:12.730
so that when they see it in school,

00:27:12.730 --> 00:27:14.810
they've already had some exposure.

00:27:14.810 --> 00:27:18.233
The other thing I would say
is, "Don't overschedule them."

00:27:18.233 --> 00:27:20.839
I mean, I think sometimes the
same parents that would, you know,

00:27:21.485 --> 00:27:24.118
the same parents that would
do the teaching ahead of time,

00:27:24.118 --> 00:27:25.869
the same time, will also,
"You have piano lessons.

00:27:25.869 --> 00:27:27.631
"You have soccer lessons.
You have everything."

00:27:27.631 --> 00:27:30.628
and I think there's a
value there definitely

00:27:30.628 --> 00:27:32.646
but if it's complete overscheduling,

00:27:32.646 --> 00:27:37.093
you have the loss of time for the
child to develop their own creativity

00:27:37.093 --> 00:27:38.513
kind of what I had in that GT class.

00:27:38.513 --> 00:27:41.207
Frankly, in the ['80s],
I was a latchkey child

00:27:41.207 --> 00:27:44.411
where my mom, she worked these odd jobs

00:27:44.411 --> 00:27:46.400
and would come along at 6 or 7:00.

00:27:46.400 --> 00:27:47.893
And so, me and my sister
would just hang out,

00:27:47.893 --> 00:27:51.114
some of it was wasted watching TV
but a lot of it was just this like,

00:27:51.114 --> 00:27:52.825
"I wanna build something or I wanna draw."

00:27:52.825 --> 00:27:54.997
We would make up games and stuff like that

00:27:54.997 --> 00:27:56.234
and kids need that.

00:27:56.234 --> 00:27:59.451
They need that free space and
maybe if they're blowing it all

00:27:59.451 --> 00:28:02.647
on video games or watching TV,
you need to push them a little bit

00:28:02.647 --> 00:28:06.548
or do something creative with them
but they need that time for creativity

00:28:06.548 --> 00:28:09.054
and the last thing I would recommend
is that the parents themselves,

00:28:09.054 --> 00:28:11.919
engage in learning because
you set that example.

00:28:11.919 --> 00:28:15.031
If you're 40 or 50 years
old and you're going back

00:28:15.031 --> 00:28:18.535
in learning algebra or
cosmology or English lit,

00:28:18.535 --> 00:28:20.753
it's a sure signal for students.

