00:28:55.001 --> 00:28:57.944
here in Washington and then with
the discussions on Capitol Hill

00:28:57.944 --> 00:29:02.697
but yeah, how would you
describe that vision for us?

00:29:02.697 --> 00:29:05.800
Sal: (laughs)

00:29:05.800 --> 00:29:09.841
which is not gonna be popular but
yeah, let's delve into this a bit.

00:29:09.841 --> 00:29:10.916
Sal: Yeah, I know there's a lot there.

00:29:10.916 --> 00:29:12.801
I mean the first to mention is

00:29:14.262 --> 00:29:16.298
once you remove lecture from class time,

00:29:16.298 --> 00:29:18.087
you say class time is
time for interaction.

00:29:18.087 --> 00:29:20.016
You can have students
working at their own pace,

00:29:20.016 --> 00:29:23.182
allows you to rethink everything and
so, a lot of the concepts of this book

00:29:23.182 --> 00:29:24.224
and a lot of these are happening.

00:29:24.224 --> 00:29:25.467
I mean there's schools
that we're working with,

00:29:25.467 --> 00:29:27.894
that are doing these things.

00:29:28.694 --> 00:29:30.599
They are experiments for their experiments

00:29:30.599 --> 00:29:34.116
that all the research and all of the
intuition point in that direction.

00:29:34.516 --> 00:29:36.720
Teaching is for the most
part, a solitary profession.

00:29:36.720 --> 00:29:39.441
Nina: It's lonely profession.

00:29:39.441 --> 00:29:40.787
It's lonely, it's lonely.

00:29:40.787 --> 00:29:43.220
And so, you can have a hundred students,

00:29:43.220 --> 00:29:45.384
you're not chaining the
student/teacher ration.

00:29:45.384 --> 00:29:46.627
You might even improve it.

00:29:46.627 --> 00:29:48.546
but you now have four
teachers in the same room.

00:29:48.546 --> 00:29:51.083
Now, if one of them gets sick, students
don't have a substitute teacher.

00:29:51.083 --> 00:29:53.214
Different students are gonna
connect with different teachers.

00:29:53.214 --> 00:29:54.294
They can mentor each other.

00:29:54.294 --> 00:29:56.618
They can do group things
with the teachers together

00:29:56.618 --> 00:29:58.288
but there's a whole
dimension that you can add.

00:29:58.288 --> 00:30:01.475
You could have a physics
teacher, a math teacher,

00:30:01.475 --> 00:30:04.144
a chemistry teacher and a biology
teacher, all teaching simultaneously.

00:30:04.144 --> 00:30:06.185
Students understand
that all these sciences

00:30:06.185 --> 00:30:07.768
and these math actually blend together.

00:30:07.768 --> 00:30:09.865
They're not these siloed subjects.

00:30:09.865 --> 00:30:12.114
They get a holistic understanding.

00:30:12.114 --> 00:30:15.479
The test themselves, you
need some aspect of testing

00:30:16.185 --> 00:30:18.541
but you should be very
skeptical of testing

00:30:18.541 --> 00:30:21.489
because all test measure what they test

00:30:21.812 --> 00:30:24.634
and there's many more [process]
to a human being than that

00:30:25.126 --> 00:30:28.936
and so, the dimensions that
there could be some testing

00:30:28.936 --> 00:30:31.464
to make sure that students
are getting core competency

00:30:31.464 --> 00:30:34.357
and some core skills but
the more important skills,

00:30:34.357 --> 00:30:38.150
which I think are completely
unmeasured right now are creativity

00:30:38.150 --> 00:30:40.234
and you could never get
someone a creativity score

00:30:40.234 --> 00:30:44.390
but you can have someone generate
a portfolio of creative works.

00:30:44.990 --> 00:30:47.188
As an employer, we're hiring engineers and

00:30:47.188 --> 00:30:50.653
when we get these people
great GPAs from top schools

00:30:50.653 --> 00:30:52.435
in the country and they say,
"What have you created?"

00:30:53.188 --> 00:30:54.743
That's what engineer is,

00:30:54.743 --> 00:30:56.111
building new things

00:30:56.111 --> 00:30:57.529
and they haven't created anything

00:30:57.529 --> 00:31:00.196
because they've been on the
treadmill the whole time,

00:31:00.196 --> 00:31:03.252
just trying to finish problem sets
and they're very, very smart people.

00:31:03.252 --> 00:31:07.046
And so, the ideal is that students
over their careers can show

00:31:07.046 --> 00:31:08.042
what they've created.

00:31:08.042 --> 00:31:09.670
It's not like they write
a paper that gets graded

00:31:09.670 --> 00:31:10.805
and gets thrown away.

00:31:10.805 --> 00:31:12.800
They write a paper, maybe gets graded

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:14.087
and then they keep working on the paper.

00:31:14.087 --> 00:31:15.155
They keep developing it.

00:31:15.155 --> 00:31:16.595
When they're 18, they have a novel done.

00:31:16.595 --> 00:31:18.590
They have a bunch of papers on policy done

00:31:18.590 --> 00:31:20.177
that they can show
people, "This is my work."

00:31:20.177 --> 00:31:21.893
They have computer programs written.

00:31:21.893 --> 00:31:24.678
They build robots and on top of that,

00:31:24.678 --> 00:31:26.760
and this is another dimension,
that's completely missed

00:31:28.190 --> 00:31:30.866
in the Prussian model so to speak is,

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:34.153
as

00:31:34.153 --> 00:31:36.624
I think in any field, the people
you wanna work with the most,

00:31:36.624 --> 00:31:39.791
are the people who have deep
subject matter expertise

00:31:39.791 --> 00:31:42.129
but are also always willing to help others

00:31:42.129 --> 00:31:44.086
and they have that
communication and that ability

00:31:44.086 --> 00:31:46.256
to empathize and

00:31:46.256 --> 00:31:49.552
in our current system, we make
everyone very focused on themselves,

00:31:49.552 --> 00:31:52.511
"What are your grades? Are
you going to pass the test?

00:31:52.511 --> 00:31:55.312
"Cram for the next
exam." and then the model

00:31:55.312 --> 00:31:57.256
that we're describing, we're
starting to see in a lot of schools,

00:31:57.256 --> 00:31:59.109
let's focus everyone on each other.

00:31:59.109 --> 00:32:00.332
So yeah, you go it your own pace,

00:32:00.332 --> 00:32:01.858
you might be racing
ahead and that's great.

00:32:01.858 --> 00:32:03.927
You're stimulated, you're engaged

00:32:03.927 --> 00:32:06.351
but you also have a chance to
reengage with some students

00:32:06.351 --> 00:32:07.922
who might be having difficulty
and there's two things,

00:32:07.922 --> 00:32:09.438
one, you're gonna be helping that student

00:32:09.438 --> 00:32:12.159
but even better, when you
explain that, hopefully,

00:32:12.159 --> 00:32:14.570
and you develop your ability to explain,

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:17.408
you'll learn the material better
and you'll learn to communicate.

00:32:17.408 --> 00:32:19.743
You'll learn to empathize and
that actually is measurable.

00:32:19.743 --> 00:32:21.570
I mean you can have
students rate each other.

00:32:21.570 --> 00:32:23.739
You can have people write
assessments for each other.

00:32:23.739 --> 00:32:25.490
"Oh, you know, he understood the
stuff but he was a little bit,

00:32:25.490 --> 00:32:27.488
"you know, he spoke a little
fast." and you could develop

00:32:27.488 --> 00:32:28.655
that aspect.

00:32:28.655 --> 00:32:32.666
I'd imagine the transcript of
the future and I say the future

00:32:32.666 --> 00:32:34.351
when I mean the future
is like actually now.

00:32:35.489 --> 00:32:37.098
Yeah, you would have your test scores.

00:32:37.098 --> 00:32:38.924
Your test scores would actually
show actual competency.

00:32:38.924 --> 00:32:39.846
It wouldn't be grades.

00:32:39.846 --> 00:32:42.948
It would be like, "Yeah, I understand
algebra and I've renewed it.

00:32:42.948 --> 00:32:45.022
"I've renewed that I know
algebra well. I know cosmology.

00:32:45.022 --> 00:32:47.520
"I'm a writer and here's my writings."

00:32:48.104 --> 00:32:50.564
You have a portfolio of your
creative works in multidimensions

00:32:51.856 --> 00:32:55.358
and you have reviews from people
that you've helped saying,

00:32:55.358 --> 00:32:58.394
"Great person to work with. Really
understood the subject matter.

00:32:58.394 --> 00:33:00.870
"Really was able to communicate
well." and those are things

00:33:00.870 --> 00:33:02.933
that I think anyone would
actually care about more

00:33:02.933 --> 00:33:04.455
than just test scores.

