00:47:58.089 --> 00:48:01.249
Sal: Yeah, exact- if you go, you
know, the Prussian model started

00:48:01.249 --> 00:48:03.525
in the Industrial Revolution
and Industrial Revolution,

00:48:04.140 --> 00:48:07.152
we needed probably more
educated people than we needed

00:48:07.152 --> 00:48:08.990
in a kind of an agrarian civilization.

00:48:08.990 --> 00:48:10.818
We needed people who
could read the directions

00:48:10.818 --> 00:48:13.738
and have the discipline of the
assembly line and all of that

00:48:14.153 --> 00:48:16.586
but there's also, there's
a certain passivity

00:48:16.586 --> 00:48:18.084
that you also had to implicate.

00:48:18.084 --> 00:48:21.039
In the farm, there's a certain
independence and freedom to it.

00:48:21.039 --> 00:48:22.863
All of a sudden, in a
factory, you're doing this

00:48:22.863 --> 00:48:24.713
over and over again and

00:48:26.143 --> 00:48:28.735
one can debate whether
it was explicitly done

00:48:28.735 --> 00:48:31.258
but there was an element of
instilling that passivity

00:48:31.258 --> 00:48:35.631
in indoctrination so that
people could be good workers

00:48:35.631 --> 00:48:37.475
but now, we're [in reality],

00:48:37.475 --> 00:48:38.711
Before the pyramid was like this,

00:48:38.711 --> 00:48:40.859
you needed a few knowledge workers
who are doing creative things

00:48:40.859 --> 00:48:42.949
and then you needed a mass of labor.

00:48:42.949 --> 00:48:46.982
Now, the pyramid's kind of inverted
where we need a lot of creative people.

00:48:46.982 --> 00:48:50.069
In fact, all of the real
careers now are creative focused

00:48:50.069 --> 00:48:52.813
and open ended and you need very few,

00:48:52.813 --> 00:48:56.037
you need very little physical
labor and in that reality,

00:48:56.513 --> 00:49:00.987
we're training people for this
